ce:section.ce:para:
In order to investigate the actual weight percentage of the CQDs load, fluorescence analysis was performed on the prepared samples. We first prepare a standard solution with a known concentration of CQDs to obtain a standard curve. As shown in Fig. 3
                        , the fitting equation of the fluorescence intensity (Y) and the mass of CQDs (X) can be expressed as Y = 200.1422 + 47229.9877X, which the fitted correlation coefficient R2 is 0.9883. Then we performed fluorescence tests on Co[Ni(CN)4] NSs loaded with different CQDs. The actual loading of the deposited CQDs on the Co[Ni(CN)4] NSs was calculated to be 1.25 %, 3.12 %, 5.30 %, 14.01 %, 17.93 % and 27.22 %, respectively. It is understandable that the actual contents of deposited CQDs on Co[Ni(CN)4] NSs were much less than the adding amount. We speculate that the phenomenon may be due to the great solubility of CQDs in water and methanol. To demonstrate their application potentials in electronic devices, Co[Ni(CN)4] NSs loaded with different CQDs are drop-coated onto glass substrates with ITO interdigitated electrodes for the electron conductivity measurement. By modification of CQDs, the conductivity of 2D CPs NSs were successfully improved which increases from 2.347 × 10-4 to 4.162 × 10-3 (Fig. 3). They are used as active channels in chemiresistive sensors to establish highly sensitive ammonia gas detection (Scheme 1
                        ). The gas sensor abilities of Co[Ni(CN)4] NSs and Co[Ni(CN)4] NSs loaded with different CQDs were systematically studied at room temperature (RH = 67 %) (Fig. 4
                        ). It was found that the resistance and the response of the sensor were immensely related to the addition ratio of CQDs. As the content of CQDs increases, the resistance of CQDs@Co[Ni(CN)4] NSs decreases and gradually stabilizes, while the response to 1 ppm ammonia shows a trend of “increasing-maximum-decreasing”. The highest response value of 241 % was obtained when the addition of CQDs was 14.01 wt%, which was about 2.7 times higher than that of pure Co[Ni(CN)4] NSs.

The typical response-recovery curve of CQDs@Co[Ni(CN)4] NSs and Co[Ni(CN)4] NSs were obtained by exposing the sensor to NH3 over the range of 0.1–30 ppm (Fig. 5
                        a and 5c). The theoretical detection limit (LOD) of the Co[Ni(CN)4] NSs (∼85 ppb) and CQDs@Co[Ni(CN)4] NSs (∼8 ppb) sensor are calculated using the following formula: LOD = 3σ/b, where σ is the standard deviation of the response within 100 s, b is the response value. In addition, the response value of CQDs@Co[Ni(CN)4] NSs to 1 ppm NH3 is 3.41. It is worth noting that this response is the highest response value among the reported RT sensor (Table 1
                        ). As shown in the fitting curve of Fig. 5, both sensor responses have a good linear relationship with ammonia concentration. However, comparing the fitting coefficients of CQDs@Co[Ni(CN)4] NSs sensor (2.8700) and Co[Ni(CN)4] NSs sensor (2.6429) (Fig. 5b and 5d), we can also find that the CQDs@Co[Ni(CN)4] NSs sensor is more sensitive to NH3. Fig. 3e depicts the repeatability of the CQDs@Co[Ni(CN)4] NSs sensor and the Co[Ni(CN)4] NSs sensor to various concentration NH3 gas. Repeatability measurements show excellent consistency and repeatability for both Co[Ni(CN)4] NSs sensor and CQDs@Co[Ni(CN)4] NSs sensor. The cross response value of CQDs@Co[Ni(CN)4] NSs and Co[Ni(CN)4] NSs sensors to common reducing gases (5 ppm) are shown in Fig. 3f. The sensors show that the responses to most of these gases are much lower than for NH3 (10.23 and 7.18 correspond to CQDs@Co[Ni(CN)4] NSs and Co[Ni(CN)4] NSs sensors, respectively). Even for highly reactive gas molecules such as acetone and methanol, the response is only 2.60, 2.41 (CQDs@Co[Ni(CN)4] NSs sensor) and 1.98, 2.07 (Co[Ni(CN)4] NSs sensor), respectively. Therefore, the NH3 sensor can be applied to ammonia leakage detection.
